6.1 Answer Key


Code
# Amplify the effect: use only 100 rows to make sampling variation more visible
small_data &lt;- mail_data |&gt; slice_sample(n = 100)

unstrat_small &lt;- map_dbl(1:100, function(s) {
  set.seed(s)
  sp &lt;- initial_split(small_data, prop = 0.80)
  mean(testing(sp)$responded == "yes")
})

strat_small &lt;- map_dbl(1:100, function(s) {
  set.seed(s)
  sp &lt;- initial_split(small_data, prop = 0.80, strata = responded)
  mean(testing(sp)$responded == "yes")
})

# Compare
tibble(
  type = c(rep("unstratified", 100), rep("stratified", 100)),
  rate = c(unstrat_small, strat_small)
) |&gt;
  group_by(type) |&gt;
  summarise(
    mean = mean(rate),
    sd = sd(rate),
    min = min(rate),
    max = max(rate)
  )

7.1 Answer Key


Code
# Correct: prep on training
prep_train &lt;- prep(mail_rec)
norm_train &lt;- tidy(prep_train, number = 3) |&gt;
  filter(terms == "income") |&gt;
  select(terms, statistic, value) |&gt;
  mutate(source = "correct (prep on train)")

# Incorrect: prep on test (data leakage)
prep_test &lt;- prep(mail_rec, training = mail_test)
norm_test &lt;- tidy(prep_test, number = 3) |&gt;
  filter(terms == "income") |&gt;
  select(terms, statistic, value) |&gt;
  mutate(source = "leakage (prep on test)")

bind_rows(norm_train, norm_test) |&gt;
  pivot_wider(names_from = source, values_from = value)

Why “Recipe”?




A recipe is a written plan for transforming raw ingredients into something usable — before any cooking happens.


recipe(responded ~ ., data = mail_train) |&gt;
  step_impute_median(...) |&gt;
  step_log(...) |&gt;
  step_normalize(...) |&gt;
  step_dummy(...) |&gt;
  step_zv(...)


Nothing is computed yet — step_*() calls just declare the plan. That’s the whole idea.

Why Bundle Them?




A workflow() pairs a recipe with a model spec so they’re always fit and applied together.


No chance of forgetting to preprocess new data the same way you preprocessed training data.

workflow() |&gt;
  add_recipe(mail_rec) |&gt;
  add_model(lr_spec)
